\u2013 plastics); ESRS E3-4 (water body ecological status); ESRS E4-5 (aquatic ecosystem condition)", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "India is among world's top sources of plastic river pollution. CPCB and SPCBs monitor water quality; satellite algal bloom mapping applicable to Chilika, Vembanad, Wular and other Ramsar sites.", "Darukaa_status": "prototype", "input_data_required": "Sentinel-2 spectral indices (FAI, MCI), river connectivity models, solid waste data", "open_data_sources": ["CPCB water quality India", "Sentinel-2 MSI", "Lebreton et al. plastic river input model", "ISRO SAC water quality", "Ramsar India wetland data"], "access_type": "mixed", "computation_complexity": "medium", "example_use_case": "A FMCG company maps algal bloom intensity in water bodies within its sourcing watershed using Sentinel-2 to disclose freshwater ecosystem condition and eutrophication risks under ESRS E3-4.", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "Floating Algae (FAI) Range Delta", "category": "Water quantity & quality", "sub_category": "aquatic pollution & contamination", "short_description": "Floating algae change between two annual periods", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-E (Evaluate): aquatic pollution as ecosystem condition threat; Impact", "TNFD_metric_type": "impacts \u2013 water quality / aquatic pollution", "TNFD_code": "C5.0", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Freshwater/Ocean; Steps: Assess, Track; Pressure: pollution \u2013 plastics, algal blooms; metric: bloom frequency, plastic load", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E2-4 (substances of concern \u2013 plastics); ESRS E3-4 (water body ecological status); ESRS E4-5 (aquatic ecosystem condition)", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "India is among world's top sources of plastic river pollution. CPCB and SPCBs monitor water quality; satellite algal bloom mapping applicable to Chilika, Vembanad, Wular and other Ramsar sites.", "Darukaa_status": "prototype", "input_data_required": "Sentinel-2 spectral indices (FAI, MCI), river connectivity models, solid waste data", "open_data_sources": ["CPCB water quality India", "Sentinel-2 MSI", "Lebreton et al. plastic river input model", "ISRO SAC water quality", "Ramsar India wetland data"], "access_type": "mixed", "computation_complexity": "medium", "example_use_case": "A FMCG company maps algal bloom intensity in water bodies within its sourcing watershed using Sentinel-2 to disclose freshwater ecosystem condition and eutrophication risks under ESRS E3-4.", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "Algal Bloom Intensity (MCI)", "category": "Water quantity & quality", "sub_category": "aquatic pollution & contamination", "short_description": "Maximum Chlorophyll Index detecting and quantifying intense algal blooms", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-E (Evaluate): aquatic pollution as ecosystem condition threat; Impact", "TNFD_metric_type": "impacts \u2013 water quality / aquatic pollution", "TNFD_code": "C5.0 | C2.1", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Freshwater/Ocean; Steps: Assess, Track; Pressure: pollution \u2013 plastics, algal blooms; metric: bloom frequency, plastic load", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E2-4 (substances of concern \u2013 plastics); ESRS E3-4 (water body ecological status); ESRS E4-5 (aquatic ecosystem condition)", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "India is among world's top sources of plastic river pollution. CPCB and SPCBs monitor water quality; satellite algal bloom mapping applicable to Chilika, Vembanad, Wular and other Ramsar sites.", "Darukaa_status": "prototype", "input_data_required": "Sentinel-2 spectral indices (FAI, MCI), river connectivity models, solid waste data", "open_data_sources": ["CPCB water quality India", "Sentinel-2 MSI", "Lebreton et al. plastic river input model", "ISRO SAC water quality", "Ramsar India wetland data"], "access_type": "mixed", "computation_complexity": "medium", "example_use_case": "A FMCG company maps algal bloom intensity in water bodies within its sourcing watershed using Sentinel-2 to disclose freshwater ecosystem condition and eutrophication risks under ESRS E3-4.", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "Algal Bloom Intensity (MCI) Annual Range", "category": "Water quantity & quality", "sub_category": "aquatic pollution & contamination", "short_description": "Annual mean of algal bloom intensity over the selected period", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-E (Evaluate): aquatic pollution as ecosystem condition threat; Impact", "TNFD_metric_type": "impacts \u2013 water quality / aquatic pollution", "TNFD_code": "C2.1", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Freshwater/Ocean; Steps: Assess, Track; Pressure: pollution \u2013 plastics, algal blooms; metric: bloom frequency, plastic load", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E2-4 (substances of concern \u2013 plastics); ESRS E3-4 (water body ecological status); ESRS E4-5 (aquatic ecosystem condition)", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "India is among world's top sources of plastic river pollution. CPCB and SPCBs monitor water quality; satellite algal bloom mapping applicable to Chilika, Vembanad, Wular and other Ramsar sites.", "Darukaa_status": "prototype", "input_data_required": "Sentinel-2 spectral indices (FAI, MCI), river connectivity models, solid waste data", "open_data_sources": ["CPCB water quality India", "Sentinel-2 MSI", "Lebreton et al. plastic river input model", "ISRO SAC water quality", "Ramsar India wetland data"], "access_type": "mixed", "computation_complexity": "medium", "example_use_case": "A FMCG company maps algal bloom intensity in water bodies within its sourcing watershed using Sentinel-2 to disclose freshwater ecosystem condition and eutrophication risks under ESRS E3-4.", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "Water Occurrence", "category": "Water quantity & quality", "sub_category": "surface water extent", "short_description": "Percentage of time a pixel was covered by water (1984\u20132021, JRC, 30 m)", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-E (Evaluate): surface water availability as ecosystem condition; LEAP-L (Locate): locate surface water bodies; Dependency", "TNFD_metric_type": "ecosystem condition \u2013 freshwater extent", "TNFD_code": "C5.0 | C3.0", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Freshwater; Steps: Assess, Track; Pressure: water extraction, land change; metric: surface water area trend", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E3-4 (water body condition targets); ESRS E4-5 (freshwater ecosystem extent)", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "JRC Global Surface Water product (1984\u2013present) freely available on GEE. ISRO Bhuvan water body atlas maps 5M+ Indian water bodies. Seasonal dynamics critical in monsoon-driven India.", "Darukaa_status": "available", "input_data_required": "Landsat archive, Sentinel-2, NDWI time series", "open_data_sources": ["JRC Global Surface Water (Google EE)", "ISRO Bhuvan Water Body Atlas", "MODIS MOD44W", "ESA WorldCover water class", "NRSC wetland inventory"], "access_type": "open", "computation_complexity": "low", "example_use_case": "A hydropower company tracks seasonal surface water extent changes at reservoir sites in Karnataka using JRC data, disclosing freshwater ecosystem condition under ESRS E3-4 and TNFD Evaluate.", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "Surface Water Transition", "category": "Water quantity & quality", "sub_category": "surface water extent", "short_description": "Changes in surface water permanence over time (permanent, seasonal, lost, new)", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-E (Evaluate): surface water availability as ecosystem condition; LEAP-L (Locate): locate surface water bodies; Dependency", "TNFD_metric_type": "ecosystem condition \u2013 freshwater extent", "TNFD_code": "C3.0", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Freshwater; Steps: Assess, Track; Pressure: water extraction, land change; metric: surface water area trend", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E3-4 (water body condition targets); ESRS E4-5 (freshwater ecosystem extent)", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "JRC Global Surface Water product (1984\u2013present) freely available on GEE. ISRO Bhuvan water body atlas maps 5M+ Indian water bodies. Seasonal dynamics critical in monsoon-driven India.", "Darukaa_status": "available", "input_data_required": "Landsat archive, Sentinel-2, NDWI time series", "open_data_sources": ["JRC Global Surface Water (Google EE)", "ISRO Bhuvan Water Body Atlas", "MODIS MOD44W", "ESA WorldCover water class", "NRSC wetland inventory"], "access_type": "open", "computation_complexity": "low", "example_use_case": "A hydropower company tracks seasonal surface water extent changes at reservoir sites in Karnataka using JRC data, disclosing freshwater ecosystem condition under ESRS E3-4 and TNFD Evaluate.", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "Natural Habitat Extent", "category": "Biodiversity & ecosystems", "sub_category": "habitat extent & condition", "short_description": "Proportion of the landscape under natural or semi-natural vegetation cover, including forests, grasslands, wetlands, and shrublands, derived from land cover classification.", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-E (Evaluate): dependency and impact on ecosystem extent; LEAP-L (Locate): spatial screening for priority locations", "TNFD_metric_type": "ecosystem condition \u2013 habitat extent", "TNFD_code": "C5.0 | C1.0", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Land | Step: Assess (baseline habitat extent) + Track (annual change monitoring) | Pressure: land-use change, habitat degradation | Metric: % natural cover as biodiversity state indicator", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E4-5 (state of biodiversity and ecosystems \u2013 habitat extent); ESRS E4-2 (action plans for biodiversity); ESRS E4-4 (restoration targets)", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "Directly measurable using ISRO/NRSC LULC 1:50K (Bhuvan portal), ESA WorldCover 10m, and FSI forest cover maps. Covers all 12 biogeographic zones of India. Critical for sectors with land footprints in forest fringes, Western Ghats, Northeast India, and Eastern Himalayas \u2014 all biodiversity hotspots. Regulatory relevance: MoEFCC Ecologically Sensitive Areas (ESA) and Forest Rights Act. BRSR-material for companies disclosing land use and ecosystem dependencies.", "Darukaa_status": "available", "input_data_required": "Land cover classification (multi-year), ecosystem type mapping, IUCN Global Ecosystem Typology reference", "open_data_sources": ["ESA WorldCover 10m (annual)", "ISRO/NRSC Bhuvan LULC 1:50K", "FSI Forest Cover Report (biennial)", "Google Dynamic World 10m", "Copernicus Global Land Service"], "access_type": "open", "computation_complexity": "low", "example_use_case": "A cement manufacturer in Rajasthan discloses natural habitat extent within a 10 km buffer of quarry sites to fulfil TNFD C5.0 and ESRS E4-5 requirements under its BRSR Core ESG reporting.", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "Forest Landscape Integrity Index (FLII)", "category": "Biodiversity & ecosystems", "sub_category": "forest integrity & condition", "short_description": "Continuous index (0\u201310) measuring the degree to which forest landscapes remain ecologically intact, accounting for human pressure, degradation, and landscape context at 300m resolution.", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-E (Evaluate): ecosystem condition assessment for forested landscapes; LEAP-L (Locate): screening for high-integrity forest priority locations", "TNFD_metric_type": "ecosystem condition \u2013 forest integrity", "TNFD_code": "C5.0 | C1.1", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Land | Step: Assess (forest ecosystem baseline) + Interpret (materiality of forest degradation) | Pressure: land-use change, habitat degradation, fragmentation | Metric: FLII score as proxy for forest ecosystem condition and connectivity", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E4-5 (state of ecosystems \u2013 forest condition); ESRS E4-3 (biodiversity targets including no-net-loss commitments); ESRS E4-1 (policies on forests and deforestation)", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "India has ~21.7% forest cover (FSI 2023) distributed across ecologically diverse zones including Western Ghats, Eastern Himalayas, Central Indian forests, and Andaman Islands. FLII scores available globally at 300m via Grantham et al. (2020) dataset. Critical for forestry, paper & pulp, tea/coffee plantations, and mining sectors. Relevant to India's NDC commitment of 2.5\u20133 billion tonne additional carbon sink by 2030. Tracks against India State of Forest Report baselines.", "Darukaa_status": "available", "input_data_required": "FLII global dataset (Grantham et al. 2020, available via GFW), land cover, human footprint layers, forest fragmentation analysis", "open_data_sources": ["Global Forest Watch FLII dataset", "Hansen et al. Global Forest Change (UMD/Google)", "ESA CCI Land Cover", "ISRO/NRSC forest cover maps", "Copernicus Sentinel-2"], "access_type": "open", "computation_complexity": "medium", "example_use_case": "A paper and pulp company with sourcing across Central India uses FLII scores to screen supply chain landscapes for deforestation-free commitments, supporting TNFD LEAP-E and ESRS E4 disclosures.", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "Threatened Species Richness", "category": "Biodiversity & ecosystems", "sub_category": "species threat status", "short_description": "Count of IUCN Red List Critically Endangered (CR), Endangered (EN), and Vulnerable (VU) species with known ranges overlapping a given site, derived from species distribution data.", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-E (Evaluate): species-level biodiversity impact and dependency assessment; LEAP-L (Locate): priority location identification based on threatened species presence", "TNFD_metric_type": "ecosystem condition \u2013 species extinction risk", "TNFD_code": "C5.0", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Land | Freshwater | Step: Assess (species baseline) + Prioritise (high-impact site identification) | Pressure: land-use change, pollution, climate change | Metric: threatened species richness as primary biodiversity state indicator aligned to GBF Target 4", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E4-5 (state of biodiversity \u2013 species at risk); ESRS E4-2 (species-level action plans); ESRS E4-3 (targets for threatened species)", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "India hosts ~91,000 animal and ~45,500 plant species, with significant numbers on the IUCN Red List including Bengal Tiger, Asiatic Lion, Indian Elephant, Ganges River Dolphin, and Great Indian Bustard. WII (Wildlife Institute of India) maintains range maps for Indian threatened species. IBAT (Integrated Biodiversity Assessment Tool) provides site-level screening. Directly relevant to EIA requirements under MoEFCC \u2014 proximity to threatened species habitat is a clearance criterion. SEBI BRSR Core requires disclosure of biodiversity impacts.", "Darukaa_status": "available", "input_data_required": "IUCN Red List species range polygons, site boundary coordinates, species distribution models", "open_data_sources": ["IUCN Red List spatial data", "GBIF species occurrence data", "WII Protected Area network GIS", "IBAT (subscription)", "Birdlife International IBA layer"], "access_type": "mixed", "computation_complexity": "low", "example_use_case": "A hydropower developer in Uttarakhand runs threatened species richness screening against IUCN range maps to identify CR/EN species overlap before EIA submission, disclosing results under TNFD LEAP-L and ESRS E4-5.", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "Small-Ranged and Endemic Species Richness", "category": "Biodiversity & ecosystems", "sub_category": "species endemism & rarity", "short_description": "Number of geographically restricted species \u2014 those with global ranges below a defined threshold (typically 50,000 km\u00b2) \u2014 present within or adjacent to a site, indicating irreplaceable biodiversity.", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-E (Evaluate): irreversibility of biodiversity impact assessment; LEAP-L (Locate): identification of areas with irreplaceable species assemblages", "TNFD_metric_type": "ecosystem condition \u2013 species rarity and endemism", "TNFD_code": "C5.0", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Land | Freshwater | Step: Assess + Prioritise | Pressure: land-use change, habitat degradation | Metric: endemic species richness as indicator of irreplaceable biodiversity aligned to SBTN biodiversity target-setting for land", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E4-5 (species state \u2013 rare and endemic taxa); ESRS E4-3 (targets for irreplaceable ecosystems); ESRS E4-2 (action plans for endemic species habitats)", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "India is a megadiverse country with exceptionally high endemism \u2014 the Western Ghats alone has >5,000 endemic plant species and hundreds of endemic vertebrates. Northeast India and the Andaman & Nicobar Islands are additional endemic hotspots. Endemic species data available through GBIF, ZSI (Zoological Survey of India), and BSI (Botanical Survey of India). Critical for mining, infrastructure, and plantation sectors operating in the Western Ghats and Northeast. MoEFCC ESA notifications explicitly protect endemic species habitats.", "Darukaa_status": "available", "input_data_required": "Species range size data (IUCN), occurrence records (GBIF/ZSI/BSI), site boundary, biogeographic zone classification", "open_data_sources": ["GBIF occurrence data", "IUCN Red List range maps", "ZSI checklist portals", "BSI Flora of India", "Birdlife International endemic bird areas"], "access_type": "open", "computation_complexity": "medium", "example_use_case": "A mining company seeking forest clearance in the Western Ghats reports small-ranged and endemic species richness within the project footprint as part of its biodiversity baseline under ESRS E4-5 and MoEFCC EIA requirements.", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "Functional Guild Diversity", "category": "Biodiversity & ecosystems", "sub_category": "functional biodiversity", "short_description": "Diversity of ecological functional roles \u2014 trophic guilds, feeding strategies, habitat specialists \u2014 within a species community, reflecting ecosystem resilience and functional redundancy beyond species counts alone.", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-E (Evaluate): ecosystem function and service dependency assessment, reflecting ecological complexity beyond species richness", "TNFD_metric_type": "ecosystem condition \u2013 functional diversity", "TNFD_code": "C5.0", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Land | Freshwater | Step: Assess (ecosystem function baseline) + Track (functional community change) | Pressure: habitat degradation, pollution, invasive species | Metric: functional diversity indices as advanced ecosystem condition indicator", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E4-5 (ecosystem condition \u2013 functional integrity); ESRS E4-2 (action plans addressing ecosystem function); supports ecosystem service dependency disclosure under ESRS E4", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "Particularly relevant for monitoring pollination services (bee and butterfly guilds), seed dispersal (frugivorous birds and mammals), pest regulation (insectivorous birds and bats), and nutrient cycling (detritivores and decomposers). Bioacoustic monitoring using Darukaa's PollyX sensors can capture functional guild signatures \u2014 insectivorous vs. frugivorous bird calls \u2014 without direct observation. Applicable to agricultural landscapes, forest edges, and plantation systems across India. ZSI and ICAR have published functional trait data for Indian fauna.", "Darukaa_status": "prototype", "input_data_required": "Species occurrence data with functional trait attributes, acoustic monitoring data, species-trait databases", "open_data_sources": ["TRY Plant Trait Database", "EltonTraits vertebrate trait database", "GBIF species occurrences", "Darukaa bioacoustic sensor data (PollyX/Spectrum)", "IUCN Habitat Classification Scheme"], "access_type": "mixed", "computation_complexity": "high", "example_use_case": "A tea estate in Assam monitors functional guild diversity of bird communities using bioacoustic sensors to track changes in insectivore and frugivore guilds as a proxy for ecosystem service resilience, disclosing results under ESRS E4-5.", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "Composite Extinction-Risk Index (RLI)", "category": "Biodiversity & ecosystems", "sub_category": "species threat status", "short_description": "Weighted index aggregating species extinction risk across taxonomic groups based on IUCN Red List categories, tracking trends in collective threat status of species communities over time. Also known as the Red List Index (RLI).", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-E (Evaluate): portfolio-level species extinction risk assessment; LEAP-A (Assess): risk magnitude for species assemblages associated with site activities", "TNFD_metric_type": "ecosystem condition \u2013 species extinction risk (aggregate)", "TNFD_code": "C5.0", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Land | Freshwater | Atmosphere | Step: Assess + Track | Pressure: all five IPBES drivers | Metric: RLI aligned to GBF Target 4 (halt extinction) and SBTN biodiversity no-net-loss framework", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E4-5 (state of biodiversity \u2013 extinction risk trend); ESRS E4-3 (targets linked to species recovery and threat reduction); supports E4-2 action plan effectiveness tracking", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "India's RLI trend is measurable using IUCN Red List assessments for Indian species \u2014 currently available for birds, mammals, amphibians, reptiles, and selected plant groups. IUCN's Red List Index is a formal SDG indicator (SDG 15.5.1) used by India in national biodiversity reporting under NBSAP. WII and MoEFCC publish species status assessments that feed into RLI computation. Relevant for large corporates with biodiversity commitments and financial institutions assessing portfolio-level nature risk.", "Darukaa_status": "planned", "input_data_required": "IUCN Red List assessments (multi-year), species lists per taxonomic group, site-specific species assemblage data", "open_data_sources": ["IUCN Red List API", "GBIF species occurrence data", "WII species status reports", "SDG 15.5.1 national data (MoEFCC/MoSPI)", "BirdLife International Red List data"], "access_type": "open", "computation_complexity": "medium", "example_use_case": "A financial institution screens its infrastructure loan portfolio using the Red List Index across project-affected species assemblages, identifying borrowers in high extinction-risk geographies for nature-related risk disclosure under TNFD and ESRS E4.", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "Keystone and Flagship Habitat Viability", "category": "Biodiversity & ecosystems", "sub_category": "habitat suitability & connectivity", "short_description": "Habitat suitability score for ecologically significant species \u2014 keystone species that regulate ecosystem function and flagship species used as conservation indicators \u2014 modelled using species distribution models (MaxEnt/Ensemble SDM).", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-E (Evaluate): species-specific ecosystem dependency and impact assessment; LEAP-L (Locate): priority location identification for ecologically critical species", "TNFD_metric_type": "ecosystem condition \u2013 habitat suitability for priority species", "TNFD_code": "C5.0 | C1.1", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Land | Freshwater | Step: Assess (habitat baseline for priority species) + Prioritise (conservation priority areas) | Pressure: land-use change, fragmentation, climate change | Metric: habitat suitability score supporting SBTN no-net-loss and nature-positive commitments", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E4-5 (ecosystem and species condition \u2013 habitat suitability); ESRS E4-3 (targets for keystone and flagship species); ESRS E4-4 (restoration of critical habitats)", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "India's Project Tiger (113 tiger reserves), Project Elephant, and Project Snow Leopard provide rich baseline data for flagship species habitat viability. Tiger habitat suitability models are regularly updated by WII. Other keystone/flagship species include Asian Elephant, Gharial, Indian Pangolin, Great Indian Bustard, and Smooth-coated Otter. MaxEnt models buildable using WII occurrence data + ISRO land cover inputs. Critical for mining clearances in Central India (tiger corridors) and linear infrastructure crossing wildlife corridors.", "Darukaa_status": "prototype", "input_data_required": "Species occurrence records (WII/GBIF), environmental predictor rasters (climate, vegetation, terrain), land cover data", "open_data_sources": ["GBIF occurrence data", "WII wildlife corridor GIS", "ISRO/NRSC LULC", "WorldClim bioclimate data", "CHELSA climate layers"], "access_type": "mixed", "computation_complexity": "high", "example_use_case": "A linear infrastructure project crossing the Central Indian tiger corridor uses MaxEnt habitat suitability modelling to identify critical tiger and elephant habitat zones, informing route alignment and mitigation hierarchy under TNFD LEAP-E and MoEFCC EIA requirements.", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "Human Footprint Index", "category": "Biodiversity & ecosystems", "sub_category": "anthropogenic pressure", "short_description": "Cumulative anthropogenic pressure index integrating human population density, land use, infrastructure, light pollution, and access roads into a single spatial score (0\u201350), indicating the degree of human modification of natural landscapes.", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-L (Locate): identifying high human-pressure zones for priority location screening; LEAP-E (Evaluate): cumulative pressure on ecosystem condition and biodiversity", "TNFD_metric_type": "ecosystem condition \u2013 cumulative human pressure", "TNFD_code": "C5.0 | C1.0", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Land | Freshwater | Step: Locate (pressure screening) + Assess (cumulative impact baseline) | Pressure: land-use change, human encroachment, fragmentation | Metric: Human Footprint Index as screening tool for high-priority biodiversity areas", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E4-5 (ecosystem condition); ESRS E4-1 (policies addressing cumulative human pressure); supports double materiality assessment for biodiversity under ESRS E4", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "India's Human Footprint varies dramatically \u2014 from near-zero in Ladakh and remote Northeast, to extreme pressure in the Indo-Gangetic Plain and coastal urban corridors. Venter et al. (2016) and Williams et al. (2020) global datasets available at 1 km resolution. ISRO human settlement layers (GHSL) available for India. Useful for rapid screening of project locations relative to intact vs. degraded landscapes. Directly relevant for TNFD LEAP-L and EIA scoping.", "Darukaa_status": "available", "input_data_required": "Population density, land use, road networks, night lights, built area data \u2014 all available globally", "open_data_sources": ["Venter et al. Human Footprint (GEE)", "Global Human Modification Index (Kennedy et al.)", "GHSL Global Human Settlement Layer (JRC)", "ESA WorldCover", "NASA VIIRS night lights"], "access_type": "open", "computation_complexity": "low", "example_use_case": "A renewable energy developer screens proposed solar farm locations against the Human Footprint Index to prioritise already-degraded landscapes over intact natural habitats, supporting TNFD LEAP-L nature-positive siting decisions.", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "Habitat Loss and Land Cover Change Rate", "category": "Land use, land cover & fragmentation", "sub_category": "habitat loss & conversion", "short_description": "Annual percentage change in natural habitat extent, measured by comparing land cover classifications across time periods to quantify net habitat loss, conversion to anthropogenic land uses, or gain through restoration.", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-E (Evaluate): quantifying land-use change impact on ecosystems; LEAP-L (Locate): identifying areas of rapid habitat loss for priority location screening", "TNFD_metric_type": "impact driver \u2013 land-use change rate", "TNFD_code": "C1.1 | C1.0", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Land | Step: Assess (baseline) + Track (annual monitoring of land-use change pressure) | Pressure: land-use change (primary driver) | Metric: habitat loss rate as core SBTN land pressure metric; aligned to SBTN no-net-loss target-setting for terrestrial ecosystems", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E4-5 (ecosystem extent change); ESRS E4-3 (no-net-loss and net-positive targets for habitat); ESRS E4-4 (restoration tracking); ESRS E1-3 (LULUCF \u2014 land use change for GHG balance)", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "India's forest cover has shown complex dynamics \u2014 net gains in planted forests but ongoing losses of natural/primary forests, particularly in Northeast India, Odisha, and Chhattisgarh. Hansen et al. Global Forest Watch provides annual tree cover loss at 30m since 2000. ISRO/NRSC LULC provides classified change maps. FSI biennial State of Forest Reports track forest cover by state. IMD land use change data feeds national GHG inventory. Critical for deforestation-linked supply chains: paper, timber, palm, tea, rubber. SEBI BRSR Core requires land use disclosure for top 1000 listed companies.", "Darukaa_status": "available", "input_data_required": "Multi-temporal land cover data, forest loss/gain layers, change detection algorithms", "open_data_sources": ["Hansen et al. Global Forest Watch (GFW)", "ISRO/NRSC LULC multi-year", "ESA CCI Land Cover time series", "Global Forest Watch deforestation alerts", "FSI State of Forest Report"], "access_type": "open", "computation_complexity": "medium", "example_use_case": "A food & beverage company sourcing sugarcane from Maharashtra monitors habitat loss rate in its sourcing geographies annually to verify deforestation-free commitments and disclose land-use change under TNFD C1.1 and ESRS E4-5.", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "KBA and IBA Overlap", "category": "Compliance & proximity to protected/sensitive areas", "sub_category": "key biodiversity areas", "short_description": "Spatial overlap between a project or operational footprint and globally designated Key Biodiversity Areas (KBAs) or Important Bird and Biodiversity Areas (IBAs), indicating presence within internationally recognised high-biodiversity sites.", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-L (Locate): mandatory screening criterion for high-biodiversity sensitivity sites; LEAP-E (Evaluate): triggering enhanced biodiversity assessment when overlap confirmed", "TNFD_metric_type": "compliance \u2013 proximity to sensitive areas (KBA/IBA)", "TNFD_code": "C5.0 | C1.0", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Land | Freshwater | Step: Locate (site sensitivity screening) + Assess (baseline within KBA) | Pressure: land-use change, all impact drivers | Metric: KBA/IBA overlap as mandatory input to SBTN biodiversity no-net-loss assessment and mitigation hierarchy", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E4-5 (sensitive areas \u2013 KBA presence); ESRS E4-1 (policies on protected and sensitive areas); supports double materiality screening for biodiversity; triggers E4-2 (biodiversity action plan) when overlap is identified", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "India has 883 designated IBAs (BirdLife International) and a growing number of KBAs. IBA boundaries available as open GIS from BirdLife India. KBA boundaries available from KBA Partnership database. Many Indian IBAs overlap with Protected Areas, ESZs (Eco-Sensitive Zones), and Ramsar sites. MoEFCC EIA process requires disclosure of proximity to PAs, ESAs, and heritage sites \u2014 KBAs/IBAs are internationally recognised equivalents. Relevant for any project seeking environmental clearance near forested or wetland landscapes.", "Darukaa_status": "available", "input_data_required": "KBA polygon database (KBA Partnership), IBA polygon database (BirdLife), project boundary coordinates, spatial intersection analysis", "open_data_sources": ["KBA Partnership database (kba.iucnredlist.org)", "BirdLife International IBA GIS", "Protected Planet WDPA", "MoEFCC Protected Area network GIS", "Ramsar Sites Information Service"], "access_type": "open", "computation_complexity": "low", "example_use_case": "An infrastructure developer screens proposed road alignments in Madhya Pradesh for KBA and IBA overlap as the first TNFD LEAP-L step, triggering a full species impact assessment where overlap is confirmed, in compliance with ESRS E4-1 policies on sensitive areas.", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "IUCN STAR Metric", "category": "Biodiversity & ecosystems", "sub_category": "species extinction risk reduction", "short_description": "Species Threat Abatement and Recovery (STAR) metric quantifying the potential reduction in global extinction risk achievable through threat abatement or habitat restoration at a given location, enabling site-level contribution to species recovery.", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-E (Evaluate): quantifying biodiversity impact significance in terms of extinction risk contribution; LEAP-A (Assess): opportunity assessment for nature-positive actions", "TNFD_metric_type": "ecosystem condition \u2013 extinction risk abatement potential", "TNFD_code": "C5.0", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Land | Freshwater | Step: Assess (impact magnitude) + Act (target-setting for species recovery) + Track (measuring abatement progress) | Pressure: land-use change, exploitation | Metric: STAR is a primary SBTN-aligned biodiversity metric for setting science-based targets at the site level", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E4-3 (science-based biodiversity targets, including extinction risk reduction); ESRS E4-4 (restoration actions valued by extinction risk abatement); ESRS E4-5 (state of species \u2014 extinction risk trajectory)", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "IUCN STAR global dataset available at 1km resolution covering Indian species. Particularly high STAR values in Western Ghats, Northeast India, and Andaman Islands due to high endemism and threatened species density. STAR enables companies to quantify the biodiversity value of conservation or restoration actions in biodiversity offset or voluntary conservation programmes. Relevant for mining companies with biodiversity offset obligations under MoEFCC clearance conditions and for financial institutions structuring nature-linked bonds.", "Darukaa_status": "planned", "input_data_required": "IUCN STAR global dataset, species range maps, threat pressure layers, site boundary", "open_data_sources": ["IUCN STAR Metric dataset (iucn.org/resources/conservation-tool/star-metric)", "IUCN Red List species data", "GBIF occurrence data", "Protected Planet WDPA"], "access_type": "open", "computation_complexity": "medium", "example_use_case": "A mining company in Odisha uses the IUCN STAR metric to quantify extinction risk reduction potential from a proposed habitat restoration programme, demonstrating measurable science-based biodiversity outcomes to fulfil TNFD LEAP-A opportunity assessment and ESRS E4-3 target requirements.", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "Potentially Disappeared Fraction (PDF)", "category": "Biodiversity & ecosystems", "sub_category": "species extinction risk", "short_description": "Fraction of species in a given area potentially lost due to land-use change, pollution, or other stressors, expressed as a proportion of total species richness. Widely used in Life Cycle Assessment (LCA) and corporate biodiversity footprinting.", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-E (Evaluate): biodiversity impact quantification in absolute terms; LEAP-A (Assess): impact severity assessment for corporate biodiversity footprint", "TNFD_metric_type": "ecosystem condition \u2013 species loss fraction", "TNFD_code": "C5.0", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Land | Freshwater | Step: Assess (impact quantification) + Interpret (materiality assessment of species loss) | Pressure: land-use change, pollution | Metric: PDF aligned with LCA biodiversity impact methodology; used in SBTN freshwater and land footprinting approaches", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E4-5 (state of biodiversity \u2014 species loss quantification); ESRS E4-2 (action plans to reduce species loss); E4-3 (targets to reduce biodiversity footprint); E2-4 (pollution impact on biodiversity)", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "PDF is used in global biodiversity footprinting tools including GLOBIO, ReCiPe (LCA characterisation factors), and the ENCORE framework. Applicable in India for assessing land-use and chemical pollution impacts on species assemblages. Particularly relevant for chemical manufacturers, textile dyers, pharmaceutical companies, and agricultural supply chains operating in high-species-richness regions like the Western Ghats, Gangetic wetlands, and Sundarbans. IUCN and GBIF species occurrence data for India supports regional PDF computation.", "Darukaa_status": "planned", "input_data_required": "Species richness baseline, land-use change layers, pollution stress data, characterisation factors (ReCiPe/GLOBIO)", "open_data_sources": ["GLOBIO biodiversity model", "ReCiPe LCA characterisation factors", "GBIF species occurrence", "IUCN Red List spatial data", "ENCORE biodiversity dependencies tool"], "access_type": "mixed", "computation_complexity": "high", "example_use_case": "A pharmaceutical manufacturer in Hyderabad calculates the Potentially Disappeared Fraction of species in effluent-receiving water bodies to quantify its biodiversity footprint from chemical discharge, disclosing results under ESRS E4-5 and E2-4.", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "Ecosystem Integrity Index", "category": "Biodiversity & ecosystems", "sub_category": "ecosystem condition & connectivity", "short_description": "Composite index capturing the overall ecological condition of an ecosystem by integrating vegetation structure, species composition, soil function, hydrological connectivity, and absence of degradation pressures into a single normalised score.", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-E (Evaluate): holistic ecosystem condition assessment integrating multiple ecological dimensions; LEAP-A (Assess): ecosystem-level risk from degradation or disturbance", "TNFD_metric_type": "ecosystem condition \u2013 integrated integrity", "TNFD_code": "C5.0", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Land | Freshwater | Step: Assess (ecosystem baseline) + Track (condition trends over time) | Pressure: multiple \u2014 land-use change, pollution, fragmentation | Metric: Ecosystem Integrity Index as a holistic state indicator supporting SBTN ecosystem-level target-setting beyond single-pressure metrics", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E4-5 (ecosystem condition \u2014 integrity and health); ESRS E4-4 (restoration targets framed as ecosystem integrity recovery); ESRS E4-2 (policies addressing ecosystem degradation)", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "Ecosystem integrity data available for India through Venter et al. Human Footprint (as proxy), BII (Biodiversity Intactness Index via PREDICTS database), and FLII for forests. The IUCN Red List of Ecosystems provides integrity-based ecosystem threat assessments applicable to Indian ecosystems including the Sundarbans, Western Ghats montane forests, and Himalayan alpine meadows. Relevant for SEBI BRSR Core disclosures on ecosystem dependencies and for EIA baseline assessments under MoEFCC.", "Darukaa_status": "prototype", "input_data_required": "Vegetation structure data (satellite), species composition (bioacoustics/camera traps), soil quality indicators, hydrological connectivity layers", "open_data_sources": ["Biodiversity Intactness Index (PREDICTS/NHM)", "IUCN Red List of Ecosystems", "Global Ecosystem Assessment data", "Copernicus Sentinel-2 vegetation layers", "Darukaa bioacoustic monitoring network"], "access_type": "mixed", "computation_complexity": "high", "example_use_case": "A plantation company in Kerala tracks Ecosystem Integrity Index scores across natural forest patches adjacent to its operations over a five-year period, demonstrating no net decline in ecosystem condition as required by its TNFD LEAP-E baseline commitment and ESRS E4-5 reporting.", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "Natural Land Cover", "category": "Land use, land cover & fragmentation", "sub_category": "natural land cover proportion", "short_description": "Proportion of the total landscape area covered by native, unmodified or minimally modified vegetation types \u2014 forests, grasslands, shrublands, wetlands, and other natural ecosystems \u2014 as a baseline indicator of landscape naturalness.", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-L (Locate): landscape-level naturalness screening; LEAP-E (Evaluate): natural land cover extent as baseline metric for land-use impact assessment", "TNFD_metric_type": "impact driver \u2013 land cover (naturalness)", "TNFD_code": "C1.0 | C5.0", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Land | Step: Assess (natural cover baseline) + Track (annual naturalness change) | Pressure: land-use change | Metric: natural land cover proportion as foundational SBTN land pressure indicator for no-net-loss assessments", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E4-5 (ecosystem extent \u2014 natural vs. modified land cover); ESRS E4-3 (targets for maintaining natural land cover); ESRS E4-4 (restoration measured as conversion back to natural cover)", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "India's natural land cover proportion has declined from ~62% in 1880 to approximately 32% currently (combining forest, grassland, and wetland cover per FSI and ISRO estimates). ISRO/NRSC LULC 1:50K and ESA WorldCover 10m provide high-resolution natural cover baselines. FSI biennial forest cover maps available since 1987. Rapid natural cover loss tracked in biodiversity hotspot states: Kerala (-western ghats), Assam (brahmaputra plains), Andaman Islands. Directly material under SEBI BRSR Core for companies disclosing land footprint and ecosystem dependencies.", "Darukaa_status": "available", "input_data_required": "Land cover classification (multi-class), natural/semi-natural vegetation mask, temporal comparison layers", "open_data_sources": ["ESA WorldCover 10m", "ISRO/NRSC Bhuvan LULC", "FSI forest cover maps", "Google Dynamic World", "Copernicus Global Land Cover"], "access_type": "open", "computation_complexity": "low", "example_use_case": "A large conglomerate with diverse land assets across Maharashtra discloses its natural land cover ratio across all operational sites as a TNFD C1.0 core metric and ESRS E4-5 ecosystem extent indicator in its annual sustainability report.", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "Ground Surface Temperature (LST Day)", "category": "Climate & physical risk", "sub_category": "heat stress & thermal risk", "short_description": "Daytime land surface temperature (LST) derived from thermal satellite imagery (MODIS/Landsat/ECOSTRESS), measuring ground-level thermal conditions as an indicator of heat stress on ecosystems, workers, and communities.", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-E (Evaluate): thermal stress as a climate-driven ecosystem condition change; LEAP-A (Assess): physical risk from heat stress on operations and workforce", "TNFD_metric_type": "ecosystem condition \u2013 thermal stress; physical risk \u2013 heat", "TNFD_code": "C5.0 | IFRS S2", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Land | Atmosphere | Step: Assess (climate-driven pressure on ecosystem condition) + Track (LST trend monitoring) | Pressure: climate change (thermal stress on biodiversity and ecosystem function) | Metric: LST as indicator of ecosystem thermal regime change", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E1-9 (physical climate risks \u2014 heat stress on assets and workforce); ESRS E4-5 (ecosystem condition change due to thermal stress); ESRS S1-9 (worker health \u2014 heat exposure)", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "India faces acute heat stress \u2014 the 2022 and 2024 heatwaves (peak LST >50\u00b0C in Rajasthan, UP, Bihar) are among the world's most severe. IMD issues heat wave bulletins for 766 districts. MODIS Terra/Aqua LST at 1km available free via NASA EarthData. NASA ECOSTRESS at 70m provides high-resolution daytime LST. ISRO's Resourcesat thermal band operational. Directly material for outdoor workers (construction, agriculture), thermal-sensitive ecosystems (coral reefs, montane meadows), and urban heat island affected communities. BRSR Core requires heat stress disclosures for outdoor workforce.", "Darukaa_status": "available", "input_data_required": "MODIS MOD11A1/MYD11A1 daily LST, Landsat 8/9 thermal band (Band 10), ECOSTRESS LST", "open_data_sources": ["NASA MODIS LST (MOD11A1)", "Landsat 8/9 TIRS (USGS EarthExplorer)", "NASA ECOSTRESS (70m)", "ISRO Resourcesat-2A", "IMD district heat wave bulletins"], "access_type": "open", "computation_complexity": "low", "example_use_case": "A construction company operating in Telangana tracks daytime ground surface temperature across project sites to assess occupational heat stress risk for outdoor workers, disclosing under ESRS S1-9 and TNFD physical risk assessment (IFRS S2).", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "Nighttime Surface Temperature (LST Night)", "category": "Climate & physical risk", "sub_category": "heat stress & thermal risk", "short_description": "Nighttime land surface temperature from satellite thermal imagery, indicating nocturnal heat retention, urban heat island intensity, and reduced cooling capacity \u2014 particularly critical for urban ecosystems, wildlife activity, and community thermal comfort.", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-E (Evaluate): nighttime thermal stress on ecosystems and urban biodiversity; LEAP-A (Assess): physical risk from reduced nocturnal cooling affecting assets and communities", "TNFD_metric_type": "ecosystem condition \u2013 nocturnal thermal stress; physical risk \u2013 urban heat", "TNFD_code": "C5.0 | IFRS S2", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Land | Atmosphere | Step: Assess (nocturnal thermal ecosystem pressure) + Track (heat island intensification trend) | Pressure: climate change, land-use change (urban expansion) | Metric: nighttime LST as indicator of urban heat island and nocturnal thermal habitat stress", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E1-9 (physical climate risk \u2014 urban heat island and nocturnal thermal stress); ESRS E4-5 (ecosystem condition \u2014 urban thermal environment); ESRS S3-3 (affected community exposure to thermal stress)", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "India's rapidly urbanising cities \u2014 Delhi NCR, Mumbai, Bengaluru, Hyderabad, Chennai, Pune \u2014 show measurable nighttime LST increases of 1\u20133\u00b0C per decade. MODIS MYD11A1 nighttime LST at 1km available free. Nighttime LST closely tracks urban heat island intensity and affects nocturnal biodiversity (bats, moths, amphibians) as well as community health. CPCB urban environment monitoring supports ground truthing. IMD urban heat advisories increasingly reference nighttime temperature thresholds.", "Darukaa_status": "available", "input_data_required": "MODIS MYD11A1 nighttime LST, Landsat 8/9 thermal band (night overpass), urban land cover data", "open_data_sources": ["NASA MODIS Nighttime LST (MYD11A1)", "Landsat 8/9 TIRS night overpass (USGS)", "NASA VIIRS night lights (as proxy)", "ISRO satellite thermal data", "IMD urban temperature records"], "access_type": "open", "computation_complexity": "low", "example_use_case": "A real estate developer in Bengaluru monitors nighttime surface temperature across its urban project portfolio to assess urban heat island contribution and identify green infrastructure interventions, disclosing under ESRS E1-9 and TNFD physical risk (IFRS S2).", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "Urban Heat Island Index", "category": "Climate & physical risk", "sub_category": "heat stress & thermal risk", "short_description": "Temperature differential between urban and surrounding rural or peri-urban areas, derived from land surface temperature comparisons, quantifying the intensity of the urban heat island effect on human health, energy demand, and urban biodiversity.", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-E (Evaluate): urban ecosystem thermal stress and nature-based solution dependency (urban trees, green roofs, wetlands as cooling infrastructure); LEAP-A (Assess): physical risk from urban heat island intensification", "TNFD_metric_type": "physical risk \u2013 urban heat island; ecosystem condition \u2013 urban thermal environment", "TNFD_code": "IFRS S2 | C5.0", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Land | Atmosphere | Step: Assess (urban thermal baseline) + Act (nature-based cooling solutions) + Track (UHI intensity trend) | Pressure: land-use change (urban expansion, impervious surface growth), climate change | Metric: UHI index as indicator of ecosystem service loss (urban cooling) and driver of NbS investment", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E1-9 (physical climate risk \u2014 urban heat); ESRS E4-5 (urban ecosystem condition); ESRS E4-4 (nature-based solutions for urban cooling \u2014 urban green infrastructure); ESRS S3-3 (community heat exposure in urban areas)", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "Indian cities are among the most heat-stressed globally \u2014 Delhi's UHI can exceed 7\u00b0C; Mumbai's coastal UHI is 3\u20135\u00b0C; Ahmedabad was the first Indian city to implement a Heat Action Plan (2013). NDMC/MCGM data available for some cities. MODIS LST urban/rural comparison computable at 1km. Mission for Urban Heat Resilience is active under MoHUA. Relevant for urban real estate, infrastructure, and finance sector BRSR disclosures. India's Heat Action Plans in 130+ cities create regulatory context for UHI monitoring.", "Darukaa_status": "available", "input_data_required": "MODIS/Landsat LST (urban and peri-urban), urban boundary layer, land use classification, population exposure data", "open_data_sources": ["NASA MODIS LST (MOD11A1/MYD11A1)", "Landsat 8/9 TIRS (USGS)", "GHSL urban extent", "IMD urban temperature stations", "OpenStreetMap urban boundary"], "access_type": "open", "computation_complexity": "low", "example_use_case": "A real estate investment trust (REIT) in Pune quantifies the Urban Heat Island Index across its urban portfolio and assesses nature-based cooling potential (green roofs, tree canopy, wetland restoration) to manage physical climate risk, disclosing under TNFD IFRS S2 and ESRS E1-9.", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "Aridity Index", "category": "Climate & physical risk", "sub_category": "drought & water availability", "short_description": "Ratio of mean annual precipitation to potential evapotranspiration (P/PET), classifying landscapes along a continuum from hyper-arid to humid, indicating long-term water availability, drought propensity, and ecosystem water balance.", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-E (Evaluate): water dependency assessment and drought vulnerability of ecosystems; LEAP-A (Assess): physical risk from aridity change under climate scenarios", "TNFD_metric_type": "physical risk \u2013 drought and aridity; ecosystem condition \u2013 water balance", "TNFD_code": "C3.0 | IFRS S2", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Land | Freshwater | Atmosphere | Step: Assess (water scarcity baseline) + Track (aridity trend under climate change) | Pressure: climate change, resource use/replenishment | Metric: Aridity Index as key indicator for SBTN freshwater and land realm target-setting in water-scarce geographies", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E1-9 (physical climate risk \u2014 drought and aridity); ESRS E3-1 (policies on water in water-stressed areas); ESRS E3-3 (water consumption in arid/semi-arid zones); ESRS E4-5 (dryland ecosystem condition)", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "India spans 5 aridity zones \u2014 from hyper-arid Rajasthan and Gujarat (AI <0.03) to humid Kerala and Northeast (AI >0.65). Global Aridity Index dataset (Trabucco & Zomer) available at 1km via CGIAR-CSI. CMIP6 projections show significant aridity increase across Central and Peninsular India by 2050. WRI Aqueduct India provides basin-level water stress overlays. Directly material for agriculture, textiles, power generation, and food & beverage sectors in water-stressed regions. IMD and CWC jointly monitor India's drought conditions. BRSR Core requires water consumption disclosure by stress level.", "Darukaa_status": "available", "input_data_required": "Mean annual precipitation (IMD/ERA5), potential evapotranspiration (MOD16/Penman-Monteith), climate scenario projections", "open_data_sources": ["CGIAR Global Aridity Index (Trabucco & Zomer)", "WRI Aqueduct Water Risk Atlas", "NASA MODIS PET (MOD16)", "IMD gridded rainfall data", "CMIP6 climate projections (IITM/CORDEX-SA)"], "access_type": "open", "computation_complexity": "low", "example_use_case": "A textile manufacturer in Tirupur (Tamil Nadu) uses the Aridity Index combined with CMIP6 projections to assess long-term water availability risk at its production facilities, disclosing physical drought risk under TNFD IFRS S2 and water stress dependency under ESRS E3-3.", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "Habitat Health Index (HHI)", "category": "Biodiversity & ecosystems", "sub_category": "ecosystem condition & connectivity", "short_description": "Composite index of habitat quality integrating vegetation greenness, structural complexity, and site-level condition derived from multispectral satellite analysis, scoring habitat suitability for native biodiversity on a normalised 0\u20131 scale.", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-E (Evaluate): core ecosystem condition metric for habitat quality assessment; LEAP-L (Locate): screening for degraded vs. intact habitat zones", "TNFD_metric_type": "ecosystem condition \u2013 habitat health", "TNFD_code": "C5.0", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Land | Step: Assess (habitat condition baseline) + Track (year-on-year health trend) | Pressure: land-use change, degradation | Metric: HHI as primary habitat condition indicator for SBTN no-net-loss and biodiversity target-setting", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E4-5 (ecosystem condition \u2013 habitat health and quality); ESRS E4-4 (restoration tracking against habitat health baseline); ESRS E4-3 (targets for habitat health improvement)", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "Computed from Copernicus Sentinel-2 multispectral imagery (10m) covering all of India. Baseline HHI scores calibrated against India's 12 biogeographic zones. Most sensitive to change in forest-adjacent land uses: agro-forestry, plantation edges, mining buffer zones, and peri-urban green spaces. Particularly actionable for restoration projects (CAMPA funds, corporate NNL commitments) and EIA biodiversity baselines required under MoEFCC.", "Darukaa_status": "available", "input_data_required": "Sentinel-2 multispectral imagery (10m), NDVI, EVI, vegetation structural indices, land cover classification", "open_data_sources": ["Copernicus Sentinel-2 (ESA/Copernicus)", "NASA Landsat 8/9 OLI", "ISRO ResourceSat-2A LISS IV", "Google Earth Engine analysis-ready data", "ESA WorldCover 10m"], "access_type": "proprietary_client", "computation_complexity": "medium", "example_use_case": "A mining company in Jharkhand tracks Habitat Health Index scores within its operational buffer zone across quarterly satellite epochs to demonstrate no net decline in habitat condition as a condition of its MoEFCC environmental clearance and TNFD LEAP-E disclosure.", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "CPLAND \u2014 Habitat Connectivity Index", "category": "Biodiversity & ecosystems", "sub_category": "habitat connectivity & fragmentation", "short_description": "Landscape connectivity metric measuring the proportion and spatial arrangement of connected habitat patches, indicating the ability of species to move freely across the landscape. Derived from patch size, isolation distance, and resistance surfaces.", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-E (Evaluate): ecosystem extent and connectivity assessment; LEAP-L (Locate): identifying fragmentation hotspots in priority locations", "TNFD_metric_type": "ecosystem condition \u2013 habitat connectivity", "TNFD_code": "C1.0 | C5.0", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Land | Step: Assess (connectivity baseline) + Track (fragmentation trend) | Pressure: land-use change, infrastructure development, fragmentation | Metric: CPLAND as key SBTN landscape integrity indicator for terrestrial biodiversity target-setting", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E4-5 (ecosystem condition \u2013 connectivity and landscape integrity); ESRS E4-3 (targets for maintaining or restoring connectivity); ESRS E4-4 (restoration actions that restore functional connectivity)", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "Habitat connectivity is critically threatened in India due to linear infrastructure (national highways, railways, transmission lines) fragmenting wildlife corridors \u2014 particularly Central Indian tiger landscape, Western Ghats, and Elephant corridors in Northeast. WII has mapped 101 major wildlife corridors nationally. CPLAND computations use ISRO LULC + WII corridor GIS as inputs. Directly relevant to road and rail EIA requirements, which mandate wildlife crossing feasibility assessments. MoEFCC's Compensatory Afforestation Fund (CAMPA) increasingly requires connectivity metrics to guide restoration siting.", "Darukaa_status": "available", "input_data_required": "Land cover classification, habitat patch delineation, resistance surface (human footprint, infrastructure), patch connectivity graph analysis", "open_data_sources": ["ISRO/NRSC LULC 1:50K (Bhuvan)", "WII wildlife corridor GIS", "OpenStreetMap road/rail network", "ESA WorldCover 10m", "Global Human Modification Index"], "access_type": "proprietary_client", "computation_complexity": "medium", "example_use_case": "A national highway developer assesses CPLAND connectivity scores along proposed corridor alignments to identify wildlife crossing locations, ensuring habitat connectivity is maintained as required by TNFD LEAP-E and Wildlife Protection Act corridor provisions.", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "Avian Species Richness", "category": "Biodiversity & ecosystems", "sub_category": "species assemblage", "short_description": "Total number of distinct bird species detected within a defined monitoring area and time period using passive bioacoustic recording, providing a rapid, non-invasive measure of local species assemblage richness as a biodiversity proxy.", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-E (Evaluate): species assemblage baseline for biodiversity impact and dependency assessment; LEAP-A (Assess): tracking species richness change as impact indicator", "TNFD_metric_type": "ecosystem condition \u2013 species richness (avian community)", "TNFD_code": "C5.0", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Land | Step: Assess (species baseline) + Track (annual richness trend) | Pressure: land-use change, pollution, noise | Metric: avian species richness as a responsive ecological indicator of local biodiversity state, aligned to SBTN biodiversity target-setting for land realm", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E4-5 (state of biodiversity \u2013 species assemblage); ESRS E4-2 (action plans for species assemblage recovery); ESRS E4-3 (targets for species richness maintenance)", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "India has >1,300 bird species (>12% of global avifauna), making avian richness a highly sensitive and measurable biodiversity indicator. Passive bioacoustic recorders (Darukaa PollyX/Spectrum devices) can continuously capture avian community composition across seasons. eBird India dataset (Cornell Lab) provides national baseline for comparison. BirdLife International IBA layer identifies high-richness reference sites. Species identification automated via AI-based classifier trained on Indian avifauna. Directly relevant to BRSR biodiversity disclosures and EIA biodiversity baseline surveys.", "Darukaa_status": "available", "input_data_required": "Passive bioacoustic recordings (48kHz+), species identification algorithm, site coordinates, monitoring period", "open_data_sources": ["eBird India (Cornell Lab)", "GBIF India bird occurrences", "WII bird distribution data", "Xeno-canto Indian bird calls database", "BirdLife International IBA layer"], "access_type": "proprietary_client", "computation_complexity": "medium", "example_use_case": "A tea estate in Assam deploys bioacoustic sensors across forest-plantation boundaries to measure avian species richness as a year-round biodiversity monitoring indicator, reporting species assemblage trends under TNFD LEAP-E and ESRS E4-5 in its annual sustainability disclosure.", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "Avian Species Diversity (Shannon Index)", "category": "Biodiversity & ecosystems", "sub_category": "species assemblage", "short_description": "Shannon diversity index computed from bioacoustic species detection data, capturing both species richness and evenness of abundance distribution within the local avian community \u2014 a more sensitive indicator of community health than richness alone.", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-E (Evaluate): community-level biodiversity assessment reflecting ecological complexity; captures assemblage evenness that species richness alone misses", "TNFD_metric_type": "ecosystem condition \u2013 species diversity (community evenness)", "TNFD_code": "C5.0", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Land | Step: Assess (diversity baseline) + Track (diversity trend under management) | Pressure: habitat degradation, noise pollution, invasive species | Metric: Shannon diversity as community health indicator complementing species richness in SBTN biodiversity assessments", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E4-5 (state of biodiversity \u2013 community diversity and evenness); ESRS E4-2 (action plans for community diversity restoration); supports E4-3 (diversity recovery targets)", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "Shannon diversity computed directly from bioacoustic detection frequency data \u2014 no additional data collection required beyond the species richness workflow. Particularly informative in degraded and recovering habitats where richness alone may not capture community imbalance (e.g., dominance by generalist or invasive species). Validated against eBird India community datasets. Used in Darukaa's Biodiversity Index scoring across all field deployments including the Dumka, Jharkhand pilot.", "Darukaa_status": "available", "input_data_required": "Bioacoustic species detection data with detection frequency per species, monitoring period, site boundary", "open_data_sources": ["Darukaa bioacoustic monitoring (PollyX/Spectrum)", "eBird India (diversity baseline)", "GBIF species occurrence data", "Xeno-canto Indian bird calls", "WII avifaunal surveys"], "access_type": "proprietary_client", "computation_complexity": "low", "example_use_case": "A forest restoration project in Maharashtra tracks avian Shannon diversity annually as a recovery indicator, demonstrating that the community is becoming more even and balanced \u2014 not just accumulating generalist species \u2014 under its TNFD LEAP-E monitoring commitment.", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "Acoustic Health Index", "category": "Biodiversity & ecosystems", "sub_category": "bioacoustic condition", "short_description": "Composite soundscape index measuring the balance and quality of the biological soundscape, integrating biophony (natural biological sounds), geophony (natural physical sounds), and their relationship to site ecological condition. Derived from passive acoustic monitoring data.", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-E (Evaluate): real-time ecosystem health indicator from continuous acoustic monitoring; captures biodiversity activity intensity not measurable from satellite data", "TNFD_metric_type": "ecosystem condition \u2013 soundscape health", "TNFD_code": "C5.0", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Land | Step: Assess (acoustic ecosystem baseline) + Track (continuous soundscape condition monitoring) | Pressure: noise pollution, land-use change, habitat degradation | Metric: Acoustic Health Index as a continuous, in-situ biodiversity condition indicator complementing remote sensing", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E4-5 (ecosystem condition \u2013 biological activity intensity); ESRS E4-2 (monitoring biodiversity action plan effectiveness); supports in-situ evidence requirements for E4-3 (target progress tracking)", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "Bioacoustic monitoring using Darukaa's PollyX and Spectrum sensors deployed across India. Acoustic Health Index integrates biological sound richness across frequency bands, validated against ground truth biodiversity surveys. Particularly sensitive to ecosystem recovery in restoration sites (plantation \u2192 native forest transitions), degradation from human disturbance, and seasonal biodiversity cycles in Indian ecosystems. Enables continuous real-time monitoring without repeat human survey visits \u2014 a significant operational advantage in remote forest sites.", "Darukaa_status": "available", "input_data_required": "Continuous passive acoustic recordings (PollyX/Spectrum sensors), spectral analysis algorithms, reference soundscape baselines", "open_data_sources": ["Darukaa PollyX/Spectrum sensor network", "Xeno-canto reference calls", "Soundscape ecology reference datasets (Pijanowski et al.)", "GBIF species occurrence (for validation)"], "access_type": "proprietary_client", "computation_complexity": "medium", "example_use_case": "A CAMPA-funded restoration project in Chhattisgarh uses the Acoustic Health Index from deployed bioacoustic sensors to demonstrate quarterly improvement in ecosystem biological activity, providing auditable real-time evidence for TNFD LEAP-E disclosures and MoEFCC restoration monitoring requirements.", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "Taxonomic Dissimilarity Index", "category": "Biodiversity & ecosystems", "sub_category": "species assemblage", "short_description": "Measure of compositional divergence between the observed species community and a reference or historical assemblage, indicating how much the community has shifted from its baseline state due to disturbance, degradation, or succession.", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-E (Evaluate): detecting community-level biodiversity change beyond simple richness trends; provides direction and magnitude of assemblage shift from reference condition", "TNFD_metric_type": "ecosystem condition \u2013 community compositional change", "TNFD_code": "C5.0", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Land | Step: Assess (baseline community composition) + Track (compositional drift over monitoring periods) | Pressure: habitat degradation, invasive species, pollution | Metric: Taxonomic Dissimilarity as a sensitive indicator of ecosystem condition change and biodiversity response to management", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E4-5 (ecosystem condition \u2013 community composition integrity); ESRS E4-2 (monitoring effectiveness of biodiversity action plans); ESRS E4-4 (restoration success measured by community convergence toward reference state)", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "Computed from Darukaa's bioacoustic monitoring dataset using Bray-Curtis or Jaccard dissimilarity against established reference assemblages. Particularly useful for tracking restoration trajectories \u2014 does the recovering community resemble the reference forest, or is it dominated by disturbance-adapted species? Applicable to all Indian ecosystems where baseline assemblage data exists via eBird, WII surveys, or prior Darukaa monitoring rounds. Sensitive to habitat homogenisation from plantation monocultures replacing diverse natural forests.", "Darukaa_status": "available", "input_data_required": "Current species detection matrix, reference assemblage baseline, dissimilarity metric (Bray-Curtis/Jaccard), monitoring time series", "open_data_sources": ["Darukaa bioacoustic monitoring (PollyX/Spectrum)", "eBird India reference assemblages", "WII avifaunal baseline surveys", "GBIF historical species occurrence data", "Vegan R package (community ecology)"], "access_type": "proprietary_client", "computation_complexity": "medium", "example_use_case": "A paper mill in Odisha monitoring its adjacent riparian forest restoration uses Taxonomic Dissimilarity to track whether bird community composition is converging toward the reference intact forest assemblage, demonstrating restoration effectiveness under ESRS E4-4 and TNFD LEAP-E.", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "IUCN Conservation Status Score", "category": "Biodiversity & ecosystems", "sub_category": "species threat status", "short_description": "Site-level conservation significance score derived from the IUCN Red List status of species detected at a location, weighting detections by threat category (CR, EN, VU, NT, LC) to produce a conservation value score reflecting the site's importance for threatened species.", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-E (Evaluate): species-level conservation significance assessment; LEAP-L (Locate): identifying sites with confirmed threatened species presence as priority locations", "TNFD_metric_type": "ecosystem condition \u2013 species conservation significance", "TNFD_code": "C5.0", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Land | Freshwater | Step: Assess (conservation baseline) + Track (status change over monitoring periods) | Pressure: land-use change, pollution, climate change | Metric: IUCN status-weighted conservation score aligned to GBF Target 4 (halt extinction) and SBTN species protection framework", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E4-5 (state of species \u2013 conservation significance at site level); ESRS E4-2 (action plans triggered by confirmed threatened species presence); ESRS E4-3 (targets linked to conservation of threatened species)", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "IUCN Red List status assigned per species from the global IUCN database, supplemented by India-specific assessments from WII and the IUCN South Asia species assessments. Darukaa's bioacoustic platform automatically cross-references detected species against IUCN Red List via API, computing the weighted conservation score per site. Detection of a CR or EN species automatically triggers a flag for enhanced biodiversity monitoring and disclosure under TNFD LEAP-L. Legally relevant under Wildlife Protection Act 1972 \u2014 Schedule I species detections have direct regulatory implications for project clearances.", "Darukaa_status": "available", "input_data_required": "Species detection list (from bioacoustics or field surveys), IUCN Red List status per species, threat category weighting scheme", "open_data_sources": ["IUCN Red List API (iucnredlist.org)", "WII species status assessments", "GBIF species occurrence and taxonomy", "MoEFCC Schedule I species list (WPA 1972)", "BirdLife International Red List"], "access_type": "mixed", "computation_complexity": "low", "example_use_case": "A solar park developer in Rajasthan uses IUCN Conservation Status scoring of bioacoustically detected species to determine whether its site contains Schedule I or IUCN VU+ species, informing TNFD LEAP-L priority location designation and triggering a full EIA species survey if CR/EN species are confirmed.", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "Normalised Difference Soundscape Index (NDSI)", "category": "Biodiversity & ecosystems", "sub_category": "bioacoustic condition", "short_description": "Soundscape index measuring the ratio of biological (biophony) to anthropogenic (anthrophony) sound energy in a landscape, providing a continuous real-time indicator of anthropogenic noise pressure on the acoustic environment and its associated wildlife communities.", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-E (Evaluate): acoustic pollution impact on biodiversity and ecosystem condition; quantifies the anthropogenic noise pressure dimension of pollution impact on wildlife", "TNFD_metric_type": "impact driver \u2013 pollution (noise); ecosystem condition \u2013 soundscape quality", "TNFD_code": "C5.0 | C2.4", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Land | Atmosphere | Step: Assess (acoustic pressure baseline) + Track (noise impact trend) | Pressure: pollution (noise), land-use change (road/industrial proximity) | Metric: NDSI as continuous in-situ acoustic pollution pressure indicator", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E2-4 (air/acoustic pollutants impacting biodiversity); ESRS E4-5 (ecosystem condition \u2013 acoustic habitat quality); ESRS E4-2 (action plans addressing noise-sensitive species and habitats)", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "India's acoustic environment is increasingly impacted by road traffic, industrial noise, construction, and urban expansion. NDSI computed directly from Darukaa's PollyX/Spectrum sensor recordings \u2014 negative NDSI values indicate anthrophony-dominated soundscapes typical of degraded or highly disturbed habitats. Positive NDSI values indicate biophony-dominant, ecologically healthy soundscapes. Validated against Darukaa's Dumka (Jharkhand) pilot deployment where NDSI scored 3/4 as a site asset. Particularly relevant for wildlife sanctuary buffer zones, where CPCB noise limits apply, and for EIA baseline noise surveys under MoEFCC.", "Darukaa_status": "available", "input_data_required": "Continuous passive acoustic recordings (PollyX/Spectrum sensors), spectral energy computation in biophony and anthrophony frequency bands", "open_data_sources": ["Darukaa PollyX/Spectrum sensor network", "Joo et al. (2011) NDSI methodology reference", "CPCB ambient noise standards (E(P) Rules 1986)", "WHO Environmental Noise Guidelines (2018)"], "access_type": "proprietary_client", "computation_complexity": "low", "example_use_case": "An expressway project in Maharashtra monitors NDSI continuously at bioacoustic sensor stations flanking the road corridor to quantify noise intrusion into adjacent forest habitat, informing acoustic barrier design and disclosing acoustic pollution impact on biodiversity under ESRS E2-4 and TNFD LEAP-E.", "additional_comments": null}, {"original_name": "Human Intrusion and Proximity Index", "category": "Socio-environmental & exposure", "sub_category": "anthropogenic pressure", "short_description": "Site-level index of human access pressure, integrating proximity to settlements, road networks, and agricultural land with acoustic evidence of human activity, to quantify the intensity of human disturbance affecting wildlife and ecosystem condition.", "TNFD_link": "LEAP-L (Locate): assessing human pressure context for site prioritisation; LEAP-E (Evaluate): human disturbance as a driver of biodiversity impact and ecosystem condition change", "TNFD_metric_type": "impact driver \u2013 land-use pressure (human intrusion)", "TNFD_code": "C1.0 | C5.0", "SBTN_link": "Realm: Land | Step: Locate (human pressure screening) + Assess (disturbance baseline) | Pressure: land-use change, human encroachment | Metric: Human Intrusion Index as in-situ pressure indicator complementing remote sensing Human Footprint at the site scale", "CSRD_ESRS_link": "ESRS E4-5 (ecosystem condition \u2013 human disturbance pressure); ESRS S3-3 (affected communities \u2014 human-wildlife interface and access pressures); ESRS E4-2 (action plans addressing human-wildlife conflict and encroachment)", "India_relevance": "high", "India_notes": "Human intrusion into forest and wildlife areas is a major challenge across India \u2014 documented in 97% of Protected Areas by WII. The index combines GIS-based proximity analysis (distance to nearest settlement, road, agricultural field) with acoustic evidence of human activity (vehicle sounds, voices, machinery) from Darukaa's bioacoustic recorders. Validated in Darukaa's Dumka (Jharkhand) pilot where the index identified specific pressure vectors. Directly relevant for Protected Area management plans, forest rights assessment, and EIA baseline human disturbance surveys.", "Darukaa_status": "available", "input_data_required": "Site coordinates, settlement proximity (OSM/Census), road network distance, agricultural land proximity, bioacoustic anthrophony detection data", "open_data_sources": ["OpenStreetMap road and settlement data", "Census of India village boundary data", "ISRO LULC agricultural land layer", "Darukaa bioacoustic sensor data", "Global Human Settlement Layer (GHSL/JRC)"], "access_type": "proprietary_client", "computation_complexity": "low", "example_use_case": "A biodiversity conservation project in a Protected Area buffer zone uses the Human Intrusion Index to map and rank human pressure hotspots within its monitoring network, informing targeted community engagement and buffer zone management as part of its TNFD LEAP-E assessment.", "additional_comments": null}];

